: <<'DOCUMENTATION'
To capture a single character without needing to press "Enter", you can disable the terminal's canonical mode using "stty".  
This allows "head -c 1" to immediately capture the pressed key.  

ðŸ”¹ Explanation:
- "stty -echo" â†’ Prevents the key from being displayed on the screen
- "stty -icanon" â†’ Disables canonical mode, allowing key capture without pressing "Enter"  
- "stty time 0 min 0" â†’ Configures input to not wait for multiple characters
- "head -c 1 </dev/tty" or "dd bs=1 count=1 2>/dev/null </dev/tty" â†’ Captures a single character directly from the keyboard
- "stty sane" â†’ Restores the terminal to normal settings after reading  

âœ… Advantages of this approach
âœ”ï¸ Captures the key immediately without requiring "Enter"
âœ”ï¸ Does not display the pressed key in the terminal  
âœ”ï¸ Works on any terminal compatible with "stty"  
DOCUMENTATION

stty -echo -icanon time 0 min 1
#key=$(dd bs=1 count=1 2>/dev/null </dev/tty)
key=$(head -c 1 </dev/tty)
stty sane  # Restores the normal terminal configuration

echo "Pressed key: $key"
cat <<'EOF'

This script commands:

# stty -echo -icanon time 0 min 1
# key=$(dd bs=1 count=1 2>/dev/null </dev/tty) # No read, method dd
# key=$(head -c 1 </dev/tty) # No read, method head
# stty sane  # Restores the normal terminal configuration
EOF